Intuition
A BST has a special property: its inorder traversal visits nodes in sorted order.

Instead of performing a complete inorder traversal and storing all the values, we can simulate an inorder iterator using a stack. Each call to the iterator returns the next smallest element in the BST.

Therefore, if we advance the iterator k times, the last value returned will be the kth smallest element.

Complexity
Time Complexity: O(H + k)
Initially, the iterator may traverse down the leftmost path of the tree, taking O(H) time, where H is the height of the BST.
Each subsequent call to the iterator processes exactly one node, and we invoke it k times.
Therefore, the total complexity is O(H + k).
In the worst case (a skewed tree or when k = n), this becomes O(n).
Space Complexity: O(H)
The stack stores at most one root-to-leaf path.
For a balanced BST, this is O(log n).
In the worst case of a skewed BST, it becomes O(n).

Code
# Definition for a binary tree node.
# class TreeNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.left = left
#         self.right = right
class Solution:
    def kthSmallest(self, root: Optional[TreeNode], k: int) -> int:
        stack = []
        node = root
        def bst_iterator():
            nonlocal node
            while node:
                stack.append(node)
                node = node.left
            curr = stack.pop()
            node = curr.right
            return curr.val
        for _ in range(k):
            ans = bst_iterator()
        return ans
